'''Tanaka Yoritsune''' (田中 頼庸, May [[1836]] ({{ill|Tenpō|ja|天保|12=draft}} 7) - April 10, [[1897]] ({{ill|Meiji|ja|明治|12=draft}} 30)) was a {{ill|Shinto|ja|神道家|12=draft}} scholar, {{ill|kokugaku|ja|国学|12=draft}} researcher, and samurai of the {{ill|Satsuma Domain|ja|薩摩藩|12=draft}} during the late Edo and early Meiji periods. His common name was Tōhachi, and he was also known by the pen names Unsū and Umeya.
== Biography == Born into a family of the {{ill|Satsuma Domain|ja|薩摩藩|12=draft}}, Tanaka was a nephew of {{ill|Ōyama Tsunayoshi|ja|大山綱良|12=draft}}. From a young age, he became a samurai of the Satsuma Domain and was recognized for his literary talents alongside figures such as {{ill|Shigeno Yasutsugu|ja|重野安繹|12=draft}} and {{ill|Imafuji Shinzaemon|ja|今藤新左衛門|12=draft}} while studying at {{ill|Kagoshima Castle|ja|鹿児島城|12=draft}}. Through his friendship with {{ill|Takasaki Goroku|ja|高崎五六|12=draft}}, a cousin of {{ill|Takasaki Masakaze|ja|高崎正風|12=draft}}, Yoritsune was invited to join the {{ill|Seichūgumi|ja|精忠組|12=draft}}, a group of young Satsuma samurai, but he declined.
Later, Tanaka moved to {{ill|Kyoto|ja|京都|12=draft}} as part of the {{ill|Bunkyū Reforms|ja|文久の改革|12=draft}} initiated by {{ill|Shimazu Hisamitsu|ja|島津久光|12=draft}}. There, he studied Confucianism, medicine, and other subjects. Subsequently, he specialized in kokugaku and returned to Satsuma in {{ill|1867|ja|1867th year|12=draft}} (Keiō 3). After the {{ill|Meiji Restoration|ja|明治維新|12=draft}}, he joined the {{ill|Jingi-kan|ja|神祇省|12=draft}} (Department of Shinto Affairs) in {{ill|1871|ja|1871st year|12=draft}} (Meiji 4), serving as a {{ill|Kyōbu Daikan|ja|教部大録|12=draft}} and later as a priest of {{ill|Ise Grand Shrine|ja|伊勢神宮|12=draft}}.
Tanaka continued his career, becoming a {{ill|Dai Kyōsei|ja|大教正|12=draft}} and vice-director of the {{ill|Shinto Administration Bureau|ja|神道事務局|12=draft}}. In {{ill|1882|ja|明治15th year|12=draft}}, he resigned from his position as a priest after being promoted to director, becoming independent. During this time, he became well-known for his criticism of figures such as {{ill|Tokoyo Nagatane|ja|常世長胤|12=draft}} and {{ill|Senke Sonpuku|ja|千家尊福|12=draft}} of the {{ill|Izumo School|ja|出雲派|12=draft}}. His grave is located at {{ill|Aoyama Cemetery|ja|青山霊園|12=draft}} (1-ro-17-14).
== Major Works == === Principal Works === * *Kōtei Nihonki* (『校訂日本紀』) * *Kōtei Kojiki* (『校訂古事記』) * *Shintokuron* (『神徳論』) * *(Jingū) Saijin Ryakki* (『(神宮)deity略記』)
=== Other Works === * *Sansoku Engi* (『三則演義』) * *Ume no Ya Bunshū* (『梅の屋文集』) * *Kōtei Kogo Shūi* (『校訂古語拾遺』) * *(Jingū) Saijin Teiyō* (『(神宮)deity提要』) * *Gosho* (『語書』)
