'''Tanaka Yoritsune''' (田中 頼庸, May [[1836]] ({{ill|Tenpō|ja|天保|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 7) - April 10, [[1897]] ({{ill|Meiji|ja|明治|1=Meiji era|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 30)) was a {{ill|Shinto|ja|神道家|qq=draft|qq=draft}} scholar, {{ill|kokugaku|ja|国学|qq=draft|qq=draft}} researcher, and samurai of the {{ill|Satsuma Domain|ja|薩摩藩|qq=draft|qq=draft}} during the late Edo and early Meiji periods. His common name was Tōhachi, and he was also known by the pen names Unsū and Umeya.
== Biography == Born into a family of the {{ill|Satsuma Domain|ja|薩摩藩|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, Tanaka was a nephew of {{ill|Ōyama Tsunayoshi|ja|大山綱良|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. From a young age, he became a samurai of the Satsuma Domain and was recognized for his literary talents alongside figures such as {{ill|Shigeno Yasutsugu|ja|重野安繹|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Imafuji Shinzaemon|ja|今藤新左衛門|qq=draft|qq=draft}} while studying at {{ill|Kagoshima Castle|ja|鹿児島城|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. Through his friendship with {{ill|Takasaki Goroku|ja|高崎五六|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, a cousin of {{ill|Takasaki Masakaze|ja|高崎正風|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, Yoritsune was invited to join the {{ill|Seichūgumi|ja|精忠組|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, a group of young Satsuma samurai, but he declined.
Later, Tanaka moved to {{ill|Kyoto|ja|京都|qq=draft|qq=draft}} as part of the {{ill|Bunkyū Reforms|ja|文久の改革|qq=draft|qq=draft}} initiated by {{ill|Shimazu Hisamitsu|ja|島津久光|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. There, he studied Confucianism, medicine, and other subjects. Subsequently, he specialized in kokugaku and returned to Satsuma in {{ill|1867|ja|1867th year|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Keiō 3). After the {{ill|Meiji Restoration|ja|明治維新|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, he joined the {{ill|Jingi-kan|ja|神祇省|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Department of Shinto Affairs) in {{ill|1871|ja|1871st year|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Meiji 4), serving as a {{ill|Kyōbu Daikan|ja|教部大録|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and later as a priest of {{ill|Ise Grand Shrine|ja|伊勢神宮|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.
Tanaka continued his career, becoming a {{ill|Dai Kyōsei|ja|大教正|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and vice-director of the {{ill|Shinto Administration Bureau|ja|神道事務局|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. In {{ill|1882|ja|明治15th year|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, he resigned from his position as a priest after being promoted to director, becoming independent. During this time, he became well-known for his criticism of figures such as {{ill|Tokoyo Nagatane|ja|常世長胤|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Senke Sonpuku|ja|千家尊福|qq=draft|qq=draft}} of the {{ill|Izumo School|ja|出雲派|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. His grave is located at {{ill|Aoyama Cemetery|ja|青山霊園|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (1-ro-17-14).
